import{_ as e,o as a,c as o,ag as n}from"./chunks/framework.OsDJF_Ea.js";const p=JSON.parse('{"title":"Banks and Controls","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"guides/banks-and-controls.md","filePath":"guides/banks-and-controls.md"}'),r={name:"guides/banks-and-controls.md"};function s(i,t,l,h,d,u){return a(),o("div",null,[...t[0]||(t[0]=[n('<h1 id="banks-and-controls" tabindex="-1">Banks and Controls <a class="header-anchor" href="#banks-and-controls" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Banks and Controls&quot;">​</a></h1><p>The Smart Contact Mic has no physical pots, buttons, or encoder on-board -- all control happens virtually, either through the patcher app over USB or via Bluetooth MIDI from a phone. The six-bank system organises that virtual control surface into colour-coded parameter contexts so one patch can address a lot of parameters from a small interface.</p><h2 id="why-banks" tabindex="-1">Why Banks? <a class="header-anchor" href="#why-banks" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Why Banks?&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The SCM&#39;s MIDI control window is deliberately compact: four CC slots for &quot;pots&quot; and four for &quot;buttons&quot; at any given time. A bank swaps which parameters those eight CCs are wired to. Banks matter because:</p><ul><li><strong>BLE MIDI controllers are small.</strong> A phone running a BLE MIDI app might only have four faders and four pads on screen. Banking lets those eight widgets address up to 24 different parameters per patch by switching context.</li><li><strong>The patcher UI stays uncluttered.</strong> The virtual MIDI control strip in the patcher canvas shows the four pots and four buttons of the current bank. Switching banks re-labels the strip without scrolling.</li><li><strong>Live performance switches stay tactile.</strong> Changing bank is one tap or one MIDI CC, so you can jump between &quot;mix drums&quot; and &quot;sweep filter&quot; in a single action.</li></ul><h2 id="how-banks-work" tabindex="-1">How Banks Work <a class="header-anchor" href="#how-banks-work" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;How Banks Work&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Each bank is a set of 8 MIDI CCs (4 pots + 4 buttons) mapped to module inputs in your patch. When you switch banks, the same eight widgets on your control surface now drive a different set of parameters.</p><p><strong>Bank colours:</strong></p><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Bank</th><th>Colour</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Red</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Green</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Blue</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Yellow</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Cyan</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Magenta</td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id="switching-banks" tabindex="-1">Switching Banks <a class="header-anchor" href="#switching-banks" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Switching Banks&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Two ways, depending on how you&#39;re controlling the SCM:</p><ul><li><strong>In the patcher (USB):</strong> click the bank buttons (1-6) or the left/right arrows in the canvas toolbar.</li><li><strong>Over BLE MIDI (mobile):</strong> send <strong>CC 48</strong> with value 0-5 to select banks 1-6.</li></ul><h2 id="midi-cc-layout" tabindex="-1">MIDI CC Layout <a class="header-anchor" href="#midi-cc-layout" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;MIDI CC Layout&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The SCM uses a fixed CC layout so any BLE MIDI controller can drive it without custom mapping. See the <a href="/docs/getting-started/hardware.html#midi-cc-reference">Hardware page</a> for the full table. Key points:</p><ul><li><strong>Bank select:</strong> CC 48 (value 0-5 selects banks 1-6)</li><li><strong>Pots:</strong> 4 CCs per bank, starting at CC 20 for bank 1 and incrementing by 4 per bank (bank 2 = CC 24-27, ..., bank 6 = CC 40-43)</li><li><strong>Buttons:</strong> CC 44-47, bank-agnostic (the same four CCs across every bank)</li></ul><p>Since buttons share CCs across all banks, wire each button to different module inputs in different banks if you want context-dependent behaviour.</p><h2 id="soft-takeover" tabindex="-1">Soft Takeover <a class="header-anchor" href="#soft-takeover" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Soft Takeover&quot;">​</a></h2><p>When you switch banks, parameter values do not jump to the new bank&#39;s stored state. Instead they stay where they are until an incoming CC crosses within 5% of the stored value, at which point the control &quot;takes over&quot; again. This prevents abrupt jumps -- e.g. a filter suddenly snapping wide open -- when you change context on a controller whose fader positions don&#39;t match the new bank&#39;s state.</p><p>Soft takeover applies to incoming MIDI CCs from BLE MIDI apps or external controllers. The patcher&#39;s on-screen MIDI strip updates directly when you drag it, so it doesn&#39;t need takeover.</p><h2 id="auto-mapped-modules" tabindex="-1">Auto-Mapped Modules <a class="header-anchor" href="#auto-mapped-modules" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Auto-Mapped Modules&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Some modules automatically claim one or more banks and pre-assign all their pots and buttons when you drop them on the canvas:</p><ul><li><strong>Stereo Mixer</strong> -- 2 banks (Volume/Mute + Pan/Solo)</li><li><strong>Drum Machine</strong> -- 2 banks (Trigger/Pitch + Volume/Mute)</li><li><strong>BPM Looper</strong> -- 2 banks (Record/Mix + Randomise/Pitch)</li><li><strong>PortaSampler</strong> -- 3 banks (Record + Mix + Trim/Trigger)</li><li><strong>Multi Sample</strong> -- 1 or 2 banks</li></ul><p>These modules show a coloured footer on the canvas indicating which bank(s) they own. The patcher inspector lists what each pot and button in each bank does for that module.</p><h2 id="manual-pot-and-button-modules" tabindex="-1">Manual Pot and Button Modules <a class="header-anchor" href="#manual-pot-and-button-modules" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Manual Pot and Button Modules&quot;">​</a></h2><p>If you need bespoke control wiring, drop <strong>Pot</strong> and <strong>LEDButton</strong> modules from the palette onto the canvas. Each one takes one of the 8 CC slots in its assigned bank and routes its output into whatever module input you cable it to. New manual controls are placed in the next free bank; you can change the bank assignment in the module&#39;s inspector.</p><h2 id="tips" tabindex="-1">Tips <a class="header-anchor" href="#tips" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Tips&quot;">​</a></h2><ul><li>Plan your bank layout before building complex patches. Put the most-used controls on bank 1 so you land on them by default.</li><li>Auto-mapped modules consume banks in order -- add them first, then fill the remaining banks with manual Pot/LEDButton modules.</li><li>On mobile: most BLE MIDI controller apps let you label CCs and group them into pages. Name them after the patch parameters they drive so you don&#39;t have to remember which CC is which.</li></ul>',27)])])}const m=e(r,[["render",s]]);export{p as __pageData,m as default};
